{"title_page": "W. C. Steadman", "text_new": "{{Distinguish|Charles Steadman}}\n[[File:William_Steadman.jpg|thumb|right|William Steadman]]\n'''William Charles Steadman''' (12 July 1851 \u2013 20 July 1911), usually known as '''W. C. Steadman''', was a prominent [[trade union]]ist and [[Liberal Party (UK)|Liberal]] or [[Lib-Lab]] politician.\n\n== Life ==\nBorn in [[Poplar, London]], Steadman began work at the age of eight, and in 1866 became a [[barge]] builder.  In 1873, he joined the [[River Thames Barge Builders Trades Union]], becoming its general secretary in 1879 and holding the post until 1908.  In 1890, he led a successful eighteen-week [[Strike action|strike]], raising his profile.\nIn 1892, Steadman was elected as a [[Progressive Party (London)|Progressive Party]] member of [[London County Council]], representing Stepney. In the [[1892 United Kingdom general election|1892 general election]] he unsuccessfully stood as the [[Liberal Party (UK)|Liberal Party]] candidate for [[Mid Kent (historic UK Parliament constituency)|Mid Kent]]; he lost again in the [[1895 United Kingdom general election|1895 election]] in [[Hammersmith (UK Parliament constituency)|Hammersmith]].\n\nHe joined the [[Fabian Society]].\nSteadman was finally elected as a [[Liberal-Labour (UK)|Lib\u2013Lab]] [[Member of Parliament]] (MP) for [[Stepney (UK Parliament constituency)|Stepney]] at the March [[1898 Stepney by-election|by-election in 1898]] which took place because of the death of [[Frederick Wootton Isaacson|F. W. Isaacson]] in February, who had held the seat since 1896.<ref>{{cite book\n |ref={{harvid|Liberal Year Book|1905|}} <!-- {{sfn|Liberal Year Book|1905|p=302-3}} -->\n |title=The Liberal Year Book for 1905\n |year=1905\n |location=London\n |publisher=The Liberal Publication Dept. (in association with the National Liberal Federation and the Liberal Central Association)\n |pages=302\u20133\n |url=https://archive.org/details/liberalyearbook00britgoog}} Steadman won by just 20 votes, beating the Conservative candidate [[William Evans-Gordon]] who finally gained the seat in 1900.</ref>\n\nThis meant that he now represented Stepney both in Parliament and on the London County Council, having been re-elected there in elections in 1895 and 1898.\nIn 1899, he was elected to the Parliamentary Committee (later the General Council) of the [[Trades Union Congress]] (TUC), and in 1902 he was its President.\nSteadman lost his seat in Parliament at the [[1900 United Kingdom general election|1900 general election]] to Major [[William Evans-Gordon]].{{sfn|Liberal Year Book|1905|p=302-3}}\n\nHe continued to represent Stepney on the LCC, being re-elected there in 1901 and 1904. He went on to chair the first conference of the [[British Labour Party#Labour Representation Committee|Labour Representation Committee]], but left the organisation when asked to leave the Liberal Party.  In 1904, he was elected as the [[General Secretary of the TUC|Parliamentary Secretary of the TUC]], the post which later became the General Secretary.\n\nIn 1906, Steadman again stood for the Liberal Party, and won [[Finsbury Central (UK Parliament constituency)|Finsbury Central]].\n\nHe lost the seat in the [[January 1910 United Kingdom general election|January 1910 general election]].\n\nIn 1911, he announced his intention to stand down from his TUC post, but died, aged 60, before this could take effect.\n\n=== Election results ===\n[[File:William Charles Steadman MP.jpg|thumb|120px|Steadman]]\n{{Election box begin | title=[[1895 United Kingdom general election|1895 General Election]]: Hammersmith}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n  |party      = Conservative Party (UK)\n  |candidate  = [[Walter Tuckfield Goldsworthy]]\n  |votes      = 5,017\n  |percentage = 60.8\n  |change     = 6.7\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n  |party      = Liberal-Labour (UK)\n  |candidate  = William Charles Steadman\n  |votes      = 3,238\n  |percentage = 39.2\n  |change     =